TY  - JOUR
T1  - Recombinant Uncertainty in Technological Search
AU  - Fleming, Lee
Y1  - 2001/01/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.47.1.117.10671
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.47.1.117.10671
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 117
EP  - 132
VL  - 47
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - While the course of technological change is widely accepted to be highly uncertain and unpredictable, little work has identified or studied the ultimate sources and causes of that uncertainty. This paper proposes that purely technological uncertainty derives from inventors' search processes with unfamiliar components and component combinations. Experimentation with new components and new combinations leads to less useful inventions on average, but it also implies an increase in the variability that can result in both failure and breakthrough. Negative binomial count and dispersion models with patent citation data demonstrate that new combinations are indeed more variable. In contrast to predictions, however, the reuse of components has a nonmonotonic and eventually positive effect on variability.
AB  - While the course of technological change is widely accepted to be highly uncertain and unpredictable, little work has identified or studied the ultimate sources and causes of that uncertainty. This paper proposes that purely technological uncertainty derives from inventors' search processes with unfamiliar components and component combinations. Experimentation with new components and new combinations leads to less useful inventions on average, but it also implies an increase in the variability that can result in both failure and breakthrough. Negative binomial count and dispersion models with patent citation data demonstrate that new combinations are indeed more variable. In contrast to predictions, however, the reuse of components has a nonmonotonic and eventually positive effect on variability.
